  "slug": "bouillabaisse",
  "title": "Bouillabaisse",
  "subtitle": "Provençal fish and seafood stew",
  "excerpt": "A Provençal stew of multiple fish and shellfish cooked in a saffron-and-fennel broth, served with rouille on toasted bread. The defining dish of Marseille, lavish, aromatic, and better at home than in most restaurants.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Bouillabaisse originates in Marseille, where fishermen cooked their unsellable catch in a saffron broth. The canonical recipe is documented in Julia Child, Louisette Bertholle, and Simone Beck, Mastering the Art of French Cooking (1961) and Elizabeth David, French Provincial Cooking (1960). A 1980 Marseille charter specified which fish must be included in a 'true' bouillabaisse.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bouillabaisse requires variety, at least three kinds of fish, and ideally some shellfish alongside. The interplay of different textures and flavours is what makes it a bouillabaisse rather than a fish soup. The saffron-and-fennel broth is the constant; the fish changes according to what the market has.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The traditional accompaniment is rouille, a thick, garlicky, saffron-scented mayonnaise spread on rounds of toasted bread that float in the bowl. A simplified rouille can be made by blending good mayonnaise with a crushed garlic clove, a pinch of saffron, and a squeeze of lemon. Serve the broth first, then the fish and bread separately, or bring everything to the table at once.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
