      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the broth base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the olive oil in a large pot over medium heat. Add the onion, fennel, and garlic and cook for 10 minutes until soft. Add the tomatoes, fennel seeds, bay leaves, and thyme and cook for 5 minutes. Add 1.5 litres of cold water, the saffron water, and the potatoes. Bring to a boil and cook at a rapid simmer for 15 minutes until the potatoes are just tender. Season well.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the fish and shellfish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the firmest fish first (cod) and cook for 2 minutes. Add the sea bass and prawns and cook for 2 more minutes. Add the mussels, cover the pot, and cook for 3 to 4 minutes until the mussels have opened and all the fish is just cooked through. Do not overcook, remove from the heat as soon as everything is done.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ladle into large warm bowls, making sure each person gets a mix of fish and shellfish. Scatter with parsley and fennel fronds. Serve with rouille on toasted bread placed in or alongside the bowl, and lemon wedges. A plain rouille: mash 2 garlic cloves to a paste with salt, mix with 4 tablespoons of good mayonnaise, a large pinch of saffron, and a squeeze of lemon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add fish to a simmering (not boiling) broth; total cooking time for fish is 6 to 8 minutes from the point of adding the first fish",
              "cause": "Added too early or broth was boiling when fish went in",
              "symptom": "Fish is overcooked and falling apart"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add a second large pinch of saffron steeped in warm water; the fennel is also essential, don't omit it",
              "cause": "Not enough saffron or fennel; or potatoes absorbed too much flavour",
              "symptom": "Broth lacks depth"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cover the pot and cook at a full simmer for 4 to 5 minutes; discard any mussels that remain closed after 6 minutes",
              "cause": "Not enough heat, or insufficient time",
              "symptom": "Mussels have not opened"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bouillabaisse belongs to Marseille the way cassoulet belongs to Toulouse. The word describes both a dish and a method (bouillir, to boil, and abaisser, to reduce), and the traditional version was made from the unsellable fish left after market: rockfish, rascasse, grondin. The home version uses whatever good fish is available. The Marseille charter of 1980, which defined which fish were obligatory, was aimed at tourist restaurants claiming authenticity, at home, use the best fish you can find.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
